WEBVTT

00:01.418 --> 00:02.336
Ooh, I know where they are!

00:02.336 --> 00:03.420
Oh, no, I know where they are!

00:03.420 --> 00:04.796
Over there, there, there!

00:04.796 --> 00:06.381
Did you look in the dryer?

00:06.381 --> 00:08.383
[ Stammers ]
How is this all one load?

00:08.383 --> 00:10.093
Not the time ‐‐
keep looking.

00:12.054 --> 00:13.180
[ Clatter ]

00:13.180 --> 00:15.015
Why would they be in here?

00:16.517 --> 00:18.769
[ Grunting ]

00:18.769 --> 00:20.020
[ Door opens, closes ]

00:20.020 --> 00:21.522
He's here.
[ Sighs ]

00:21.522 --> 00:22.189
He's here.

00:22.189 --> 00:23.273
What did she lose?

00:23.273 --> 00:25.609
I didn't ask.
I just like throwing stuff.

00:25.609 --> 00:26.276
My keys.

00:26.276 --> 00:27.486
Let's do this.

00:27.486 --> 00:30.822
♪♪

00:30.822 --> 00:32.199
Ha!
The purse?

00:33.283 --> 00:34.910
Maya.

00:43.460 --> 00:46.922
♪♪

00:51.260 --> 00:53.053
Shh! Look!
She's getting something.

01:01.853 --> 01:03.105
[ Light switch clicks ]

01:03.105 --> 01:04.648
I already checked in here,
darling ‐‐

01:04.648 --> 01:06.149
the floor, the cabinets.

01:07.401 --> 01:08.610
He did it again.

01:08.610 --> 01:10.279
You beautiful bastard.

01:10.279 --> 01:12.573
[ British accent ]
Cheers, love.

01:16.577 --> 01:18.495
[ Laughter ]
All right,
ding, ding, ding.

01:18.495 --> 01:19.705
Let's call this meeting

01:19.705 --> 01:21.707
of our special‐needs
mum support group

01:21.707 --> 01:22.791
to "disorder."

01:22.791 --> 01:24.209
[ Laughter ]
Right?

01:24.209 --> 01:27.421
'Cause all the kids
have disorders.

01:27.421 --> 01:31.133
So, tonight, we have another mum
joining us ‐‐ Becca.

01:31.133 --> 01:32.217
She just moved here.

01:32.217 --> 01:34.052
She's coming, actually,
at really good time,

01:34.052 --> 01:36.638
because Sunday
is my annual Oscar potluck.

01:36.638 --> 01:38.015
Carly,
who will you be wearing?

01:38.015 --> 01:39.474
Sweatpants.
Same as Hillary.

01:39.474 --> 01:41.643
Who will wear it better?
[ Doorbell rings ]

01:41.643 --> 01:43.729
[ Gasps ] She's here.

01:43.729 --> 01:44.855
All right, ladies.

01:44.855 --> 01:48.650
I want you to remember
how you felt and looked

01:48.650 --> 01:50.193
the first time
you came here.

01:50.193 --> 01:53.822
So no gasping,
and sympathetic faces.

01:57.200 --> 01:59.494
Who are you?

01:59.494 --> 02:01.538
Um, I'm ‐‐ I'm here
for the support group.

02:01.538 --> 02:02.873
‐No.
‐Yep.

02:02.873 --> 02:04.916
No, uh, are you ‐‐
are you sure?

02:04.916 --> 02:07.669
No stains.
Where are her stains?

02:07.669 --> 02:10.839
Okay, then. Hi.
I'm Becca.

02:10.839 --> 02:12.674
Yes, hi.
Hello.

02:12.674 --> 02:13.800
Hi.

02:13.800 --> 02:14.926
Becca. Hi.

02:14.926 --> 02:16.011
[ Door closes ]

02:16.011 --> 02:18.388
Well, this is
for our hostess.

02:18.388 --> 02:19.848
Oh, God, you didn't have
to buy me anything.

02:19.848 --> 02:21.850
I didn't.
I made it.

02:21.850 --> 02:23.518
Even the box
is beautiful.

02:23.518 --> 02:24.645
Made that, too.
It was ‐‐

02:24.645 --> 02:26.980
You made a box?
Mm‐hmm.

02:26.980 --> 02:30.692
You do know this
is a special‐needs
moms' group, right?

02:30.692 --> 02:33.528
[ Laughing ]
Oh, yes, of course.

02:33.528 --> 02:37.616
But we all know our life doesn't
have to become one big mess

02:37.616 --> 02:39.868
just because we have a kid
with a disability, right?

02:39.868 --> 02:41.953
[ Laughter ]

02:41.953 --> 02:44.539
Oh, my God,
she's serious.

02:44.539 --> 02:46.500
How's the pre‐party
clean‐up going?

02:46.500 --> 02:47.876
Amazing!

02:47.876 --> 02:49.753
We just looked
under this tarp.

02:49.753 --> 02:52.547
Guess what that girl‐repelling
eyesore is covering?

02:52.547 --> 02:53.423
Nothing!

02:53.423 --> 02:54.758
Serves no purpose.

02:54.758 --> 02:56.677
Wind must have blown it up here,
and it stayed.

02:56.677 --> 02:59.471
It's the most useless thing
in this house that isn't me.

02:59.471 --> 03:00.722
Great.

03:01.890 --> 03:03.392
[ Grunts ]

03:03.392 --> 03:04.643
This better?

03:04.643 --> 03:06.520
[ Door opens ]
Aww.

03:06.520 --> 03:08.271
JJ's doing
his traditional

03:08.271 --> 03:10.190
pre‐party
furniture rearrangement.

03:10.190 --> 03:11.858
Well, how about
I use the laser pointer,

03:11.858 --> 03:13.527
and <i>you</i> push
the heavy furniture around?

03:13.527 --> 03:14.778
[ Horn honks ]

03:14.778 --> 03:16.446
Jimmy, your dad friends
are here.

03:16.446 --> 03:17.572
Ugh!

03:17.572 --> 03:19.157
I don't want to play
with the dads.

03:19.157 --> 03:21.243
What's wrong with them?
They're boring.

03:21.243 --> 03:23.870
The wives are these lions
who fight for their kids,

03:23.870 --> 03:25.914
and the dads
just sit there silently

03:25.914 --> 03:27.541
waiting to be told
what to do.

03:27.541 --> 03:30.794
They make me feel tough
and lively by comparison,

03:30.794 --> 03:31.628
and that is ridiculous.

03:31.628 --> 03:32.671
[ Knock on door ]

03:32.671 --> 03:33.755
Oh, hello!
[ Groans ]

03:33.755 --> 03:35.841
Welcome.
Happy Oscar Sunday.

03:35.841 --> 03:38.427
Jimmy, you remember
Kevin and Carl.

03:38.427 --> 03:41.596
Come on.

03:41.596 --> 03:43.265
Hello, boys.

03:43.265 --> 03:45.142
Yeah, it's okay.
Go on in. Have fun.

03:45.142 --> 03:48.353
Oi, are you
wearing makeup?

03:48.353 --> 03:50.230
Wait, you ‐‐ you've had
your eyebrow done.

03:50.230 --> 03:51.982
There's two of them now.

03:51.982 --> 03:53.275
Is this because of Becca?

03:53.275 --> 03:54.860
Are you changing for her?

03:54.860 --> 03:56.236
You didn't
sit next to her.

03:56.236 --> 03:57.988
You don't know
how good she smells.

03:57.988 --> 03:59.448
No, we are a group of moms

03:59.448 --> 04:01.158
who accept each other
for who we are.

04:01.158 --> 04:02.659
Don't change
for that woman.

04:02.659 --> 04:05.537
In fact ‐‐ right,
this all going back how it was.

04:05.537 --> 04:06.746
Picture.

04:06.746 --> 04:08.623
Now, Kenneth,
put it all back how it was.

04:08.623 --> 04:09.875
But do you remember
how it was?

04:09.875 --> 04:10.959
I do not.

04:10.959 --> 04:12.294
Well,
then it was like this.

04:12.294 --> 04:13.503
Ooh, Ray.

04:13.503 --> 04:15.297
Mom, look at how beautiful
this house looks

04:15.297 --> 04:17.424
without this blight on it.

04:17.424 --> 04:20.886
Ray, you were the one
who found my keys.

04:22.387 --> 04:24.306
You know
what I'm gonna say.

04:24.306 --> 04:26.057
I'll put the tarp back up.

04:29.853 --> 04:31.938
Yeah, man, big day ‐‐
the Oscars.

04:31.938 --> 04:35.358
Nobody's a bigger
movie buff than me.

04:35.358 --> 04:39.613
"You're not the biggest
movie buff at this table."

04:42.574 --> 04:44.534
Let's find out.

04:47.078 --> 04:50.749
"What was Pierce Brosnan's
first James Bond movie?"

04:50.749 --> 04:52.584
"GoldenEye!"
In your face.

04:52.584 --> 04:53.627
[ Chuckles ]

04:53.627 --> 04:55.962
"GoldenEye."

04:55.962 --> 04:57.547
Okay,
perhaps this isn't

04:57.547 --> 05:00.217
the most inclusive
trivia experience.

05:00.217 --> 05:01.551
Hmm.

05:01.551 --> 05:04.304
How to level
this playing field?

05:04.304 --> 05:09.059
"Michael Myers' mask
was based on the face
of what famous actor?"

05:13.438 --> 05:15.774
Are you two
starting to look alike?

05:16.983 --> 05:18.610
Uh, guys, what's up?

05:18.610 --> 05:19.903
My wife said
to set up for dinner.

05:19.903 --> 05:22.155
But we have plenty
of tables and chairs?

05:22.155 --> 05:23.740
Just doing what I was told.

05:23.740 --> 05:24.950
My wife said to help him.

05:24.950 --> 05:26.117
I needed to look busy.

05:26.117 --> 05:27.410
Their eyes are empty.

05:27.410 --> 05:29.329
They'd follow
any order they're given,

05:29.329 --> 05:33.959
like lemmings marching
to their death.

05:33.959 --> 05:37.170
Any order, you say?

05:37.170 --> 05:39.297
Dads, I've spoken
with your wives.

05:39.297 --> 05:40.757
They are thrilled with the work
you've done here today.

05:40.757 --> 05:42.133
[ Exhales ]

05:42.133 --> 05:43.677
But they still have
a few more tasks.

05:43.677 --> 05:47.681
Alfonso, your wife wanted you
to sort and stack these boxes...

05:47.681 --> 05:48.682
for the party.

05:48.682 --> 05:50.016
Got it, boss.
Wow.

05:50.016 --> 05:51.852
Carl,
your wife wanted to know

05:51.852 --> 05:53.478
if you could fix
the garage door

05:53.478 --> 05:55.272
to keep it
from squeaking.
I'm on it.

05:55.272 --> 05:57.023
Kevin, you can start
sweeping the floor.
Sure thing.

05:57.023 --> 05:59.234
Sanjey, this car
hasn't worked in 10 years.

05:59.234 --> 06:02.070
Can you fix it
for special‐needs reasons?

06:02.070 --> 06:03.864
Of course.

06:03.864 --> 06:05.031
I got to expand this list.

06:05.031 --> 06:06.533
Maya: Okay, everyone.

06:06.533 --> 06:08.243
I don't want to start a stampede
like last time.

06:08.243 --> 06:10.036
Pigs in blankets!
Move, move.

06:10.036 --> 06:11.621
Becca: Ding‐dong.

06:11.621 --> 06:13.290
Oh, hello, Becca.

06:13.290 --> 06:14.374
Hello.

06:14.374 --> 06:16.543
Uh, this is Savannah,
my youngest.

06:16.543 --> 06:18.628
And that's Dale.
He's my oldest.

06:18.628 --> 06:20.422
Ha!
He's my husband.

06:20.422 --> 06:21.965
[ Chuckles ]
I was kidding.

06:23.675 --> 06:26.177
Strong one ‐‐
he'll do just fine.

06:26.177 --> 06:27.220
Well, Becca,
you're just in time

06:27.220 --> 06:28.763
for one of my famous
pigs in a blanket.

06:28.763 --> 06:30.515
I'd love that,
but I'm on a cleanse.

06:30.515 --> 06:32.934
[ Quietly to Savannah ]
All right, want to go sit here?

06:32.934 --> 06:35.395
Um, but you're not.

06:35.395 --> 06:37.272
Are you standing up straight
for her?

06:37.272 --> 06:39.649
[ Laughs ]
This is how I stand.

06:39.649 --> 06:42.110
You usually look like you're
trying to lick your bellybutton.

06:42.110 --> 06:44.070
Go on, back to it.

06:44.070 --> 06:46.072
And eat that.
Slump and eat.

06:46.072 --> 06:48.617
We have guests, love.

06:48.617 --> 06:51.369
I hear you were happy
about the tarp for a second.

06:51.369 --> 06:53.830
Aw, buddy.

06:53.830 --> 06:56.625
As much as we celebrate
Hollywood fantasy today,

06:56.625 --> 06:57.959
my life is no movie.

06:57.959 --> 07:02.631
♪♪

07:02.631 --> 07:04.841
Hi.
I ‐‐ I'm Ray.

07:04.841 --> 07:06.635
Ooh,
like a ray of sunshine.

07:06.635 --> 07:08.094
Yes.

07:08.094 --> 07:09.304
That's exactly
what I'm like.

07:09.304 --> 07:10.221
I'm Zelda.

07:10.221 --> 07:11.097
Her name's Ann.

07:11.097 --> 07:12.641
Society calls me Ann.

07:12.641 --> 07:14.934
Ugh, society.
I know.

07:14.934 --> 07:16.519
I can't stand
this button‐down world.

07:16.519 --> 07:19.314
I just need to laugh
and sing and be free.

07:19.314 --> 07:21.024
Then it's a good thing
you met me.

07:21.024 --> 07:22.484
Are you a quirky
free spirit, too?

07:22.484 --> 07:25.111
No, I go by the books
and follow the rules.

07:25.111 --> 07:26.655
Yes, I'm a quirky
free spirit.

07:26.655 --> 07:28.907
Come ‐‐ we'll have
ever so much fun.

07:28.907 --> 07:31.117
I ever can't wait.

07:31.117 --> 07:32.661
Right, the show's
about to start.
<i>[ Chatter over television ]</i>

07:32.661 --> 07:35.497
I'd like to say a few words ‐‐
my opening monologue,

07:35.497 --> 07:38.583
but without the song and dance
'cause of time constraints.

07:38.583 --> 07:39.918
It's too bad, Mom.
You would've crushed it.

07:39.918 --> 07:41.336
Their loss.

07:41.336 --> 07:44.506
Thank you all for coming
to our humble gathering.

07:44.506 --> 07:48.301
The dip may be store‐bought
and the napkins mismatched.

07:48.301 --> 07:50.095
We may not
have cleaned our bathroom.

07:50.095 --> 07:51.638
Yeah, could you just go
and check the mail, please?

07:51.638 --> 07:52.597
But it's Sunday.
Yeah, but thank you.

07:52.597 --> 07:53.723
Okay.

07:53.723 --> 07:54.849
Okay, where were we?
[ Claps ]

07:54.849 --> 07:57.268
The party is perfect.

07:57.268 --> 08:01.648
Now, let's watch some Brits win
prizes for playing Americans.

08:01.648 --> 08:03.817
[ Laughter ]

08:03.817 --> 08:07.195
[ Rustling ]

08:07.195 --> 08:08.738
[ Electricity crackles ]

08:08.738 --> 08:10.782
[ All murmuring ]

08:10.782 --> 08:13.201
[ Groans ]

08:13.201 --> 08:15.036
[ Banging on television,
remote clicking ]

08:15.036 --> 08:17.706
It can't be.

08:17.706 --> 08:19.916
And that concludes
the Oscar portion

08:19.916 --> 08:20.917
of our Oscar party.

08:24.087 --> 08:25.672
Isn't our fort magical?
I'm so happy

08:25.672 --> 08:28.550
that I finally found someone
as wild and free as me.

08:28.550 --> 08:30.719
Yeah,
I'm manic pixie dream girl,

08:30.719 --> 08:31.761
like in the movies.

08:31.761 --> 08:33.221
That's my personality.

08:33.221 --> 08:34.180
Okay.

08:34.180 --> 08:35.432
Why do you dress
so weird?

08:35.432 --> 08:37.267
For me, people who dress normal
are weird.

08:37.267 --> 08:39.853
You know, laundry day.

08:39.853 --> 08:41.187
But trust me ‐‐
Shh!

08:41.187 --> 08:43.106
Why talk
when we can spin?

08:44.816 --> 08:47.736
[ Laughing ]

08:47.736 --> 08:49.779
Oh, God, Ray.
Close the door!

08:52.824 --> 08:54.534
Maya: Oh, come on.

08:54.534 --> 08:56.244
What's this?
Aw, it's frozen again.

08:56.244 --> 08:59.080
Oh, uh,
Maya's watching the Oscars

08:59.080 --> 09:00.206
and passing it along
to us.

09:00.206 --> 09:01.750
Oh, hold on,
it's back.
<i>[ Chatter through cellphone ]</i>

09:01.750 --> 09:03.668
And now the guy presenter

09:03.668 --> 09:06.296
is ‐‐ is saying
how film has the power

09:06.296 --> 09:09.382
to transport us
to faraway places.

09:09.382 --> 09:10.967
It's not working.

09:10.967 --> 09:13.720
And someone's won.
Yay.

09:13.720 --> 09:15.513
See, this is working.

09:17.098 --> 09:19.476
I've got Sanjey on hold
with the cable company.

09:19.476 --> 09:21.186
He's says
they're gonna be a while.

09:21.186 --> 09:22.437
You want to just
shut this thing down?

09:22.437 --> 09:23.646
No.

09:23.646 --> 09:25.732
These women's self‐esteem
is on the line.

09:25.732 --> 09:28.276
They need this party
to prove that the way
they live their lives ‐‐

09:28.276 --> 09:29.569
the way that
<i>we</i> live our lives ‐‐

09:29.569 --> 09:31.529
is nothing
to apologize for.

09:31.529 --> 09:33.114
Sanjey,
tell them to come.

09:33.114 --> 09:34.407
The party's become
a metaphor.

09:34.407 --> 09:35.950
Dude.
[ Chuckles ]

09:35.950 --> 09:37.827
Mad props
for knowing that one.

09:37.827 --> 09:39.370
But more importantly,

09:39.370 --> 09:42.707
who is letting you watch
"Eyes Wide Shut"?

09:42.707 --> 09:45.919
You know what? I am digging
our inclusive trivia game here.

09:45.919 --> 09:46.711
Aidan: Can we play?

09:48.379 --> 09:50.298
Huh.
Let's see.

09:50.298 --> 09:53.134
Uh...visual impairment,
hearing impairment,

09:53.134 --> 09:55.220
Down syndrome, autism,
and a walker.

09:55.220 --> 09:56.429
Hmm.

09:56.429 --> 10:00.058
How to make this game fair
for these beautiful kids

10:00.058 --> 10:03.686
instead of sneaking off and
watching "Eyes Wide Shut"?

10:03.686 --> 10:05.605
Okay,
it's a commercial break.

10:05.605 --> 10:08.024
Time to see what Lady Potluck
has in store for us.

10:08.024 --> 10:08.817
I brought cups.

10:08.817 --> 10:09.818
I brought cups.

10:09.818 --> 10:11.444
‐Cups.
‐Oh.

10:11.444 --> 10:14.489
I just did a big, huge shop,
and I bet a few of us

10:14.489 --> 10:16.324
could swing by my place,
fix up some grub,

10:16.324 --> 10:18.284
get back here
before Best Sound Mixing.

10:18.284 --> 10:20.787
That is, if it's okay
with our host.

10:24.541 --> 10:26.501
You want to ride bikes
<i>and</i> hold hands?

10:26.501 --> 10:28.837
Trust me,
it's gonna make us feel alive.

10:28.837 --> 10:30.755
You know what makes me
feel alive?

10:30.755 --> 10:32.841
Wearing a helmet.

10:32.841 --> 10:35.635
As a quirky joke.

10:35.635 --> 10:37.720
Safety first.

10:37.720 --> 10:38.847
[ Gasps ]

10:38.847 --> 10:40.431
Can we drive this
instead?

10:40.431 --> 10:42.851
Sure. If you can get
that old thing working,

10:42.851 --> 10:44.102
then we can drive it.

10:44.102 --> 10:45.311
[ Engine starts ]

10:45.311 --> 10:47.313
Holy crap.
What is happening?

10:47.313 --> 10:49.983
I feel so alive!

10:49.983 --> 10:51.901
I'm gonna wear this
anyways.

10:51.901 --> 10:54.362
Okay, now, remember, we're still
in the middle of a move,

10:54.362 --> 10:56.281
so please forgive the mess.

10:56.281 --> 10:58.408
Oh, don't worry.
No judgment here.

10:58.408 --> 10:59.450
[ Light switch clicks ]

10:59.450 --> 11:01.953
Oh, come on, lady.
[ Door closes ]

11:01.953 --> 11:03.705
Make yourself at home.

11:03.705 --> 11:05.874
How does she live
like this?

11:05.874 --> 11:07.167
Why can't we?

11:07.167 --> 11:09.252
It's making
my posture worse.

11:09.252 --> 11:12.172
God, even the floors
are beautiful.

11:12.172 --> 11:13.715
No, don't do that.

11:13.715 --> 11:15.341
She's not better
than you.

11:15.341 --> 11:17.969
Every mom has a problem.
We'll find hers.

11:17.969 --> 11:19.345
Hey, guys?

11:19.345 --> 11:23.391
It's like we've died
and gone to Pinterest.

11:25.894 --> 11:27.478
Stop trying to like it.

11:27.478 --> 11:30.607
Well, everyone has a laser
and a letter board.

11:30.607 --> 11:33.234
Aidan, your letter board is
extra large so you can read it.

11:33.234 --> 11:35.945
We'll present all questions
orally and visually

11:35.945 --> 11:37.697
so hearing won't be an issue.

11:37.697 --> 11:40.283
Since Oliver is a hyper genius
at Pixar movies,

11:40.283 --> 11:41.701
there will be no
Pixar questions.

11:41.701 --> 11:43.203
Come on!

11:43.203 --> 11:45.163
You're just like
Carl Fredricksen from "Up."

11:45.163 --> 11:46.831
I'll take that
as a compliment.

11:46.831 --> 11:49.584
[ Drill whirs ]

11:49.584 --> 11:51.294
Finished dusting
your old LPs.

11:51.294 --> 11:52.795
Ah, your wife thanks you.

11:52.795 --> 11:54.923
Took the liberty of putting
your Dukes of Stratosphear album

11:54.923 --> 11:57.717
with XTC,
since it's a side project.

11:57.717 --> 11:59.052
You like XTC?

11:59.052 --> 12:00.136
Yes, I do.

12:00.136 --> 12:02.764
Ugh, damn it.
What's wrong?

12:02.764 --> 12:04.766
You have interests.
Taste.

12:04.766 --> 12:07.477
You're like a... person.

12:07.477 --> 12:09.687
[ Hammering,
indistinct conversation ]

12:09.687 --> 12:12.273
Oh, man.

12:12.273 --> 12:14.067
[ Sighs ]
Guys.

12:14.067 --> 12:16.236
Guys.
I have a confession to make.

12:16.236 --> 12:17.987
Your wives
didn't ask you

12:17.987 --> 12:20.073
to make me a cabinet
out of scrap wood.

12:20.073 --> 12:21.616
I did.

12:21.616 --> 12:23.284
But they asked us to clean
your dryer vents, right?

12:23.284 --> 12:25.870
Also me. Same with writing
the thank‐you notes.

12:25.870 --> 12:27.080
What is with you guys?

12:27.080 --> 12:29.374
You just do anything
you're asked?

12:29.374 --> 12:32.085
My wife works so hard.
I just want to help.

12:32.085 --> 12:33.419
I want to make my kid's life
easier.

12:33.419 --> 12:36.673
Sure, get that.
But what do <i>you</i> want?

12:36.673 --> 12:39.133
[ Insects chirping ]

12:39.133 --> 12:41.594
I don't understand
the question.

12:41.594 --> 12:44.472
In the film "Pulp Fiction,"

12:44.472 --> 12:49.018
what was in
Marsellus Wallace's briefcase?

12:49.018 --> 12:50.561
Go.

12:50.561 --> 12:51.854
JJ!

12:51.854 --> 12:54.524
"Trick question.
Nothing."

12:54.524 --> 12:57.485
That is correct.
JJ for the win.

12:57.485 --> 12:59.654
Aidan: But the co‐writer
Roger Avary said

12:59.654 --> 13:03.658
that in the original script,
the briefcase had diamonds.

13:03.658 --> 13:06.869
"The question was about
the film."

13:06.869 --> 13:08.538
A film based on a script.

13:08.538 --> 13:12.166
I heard the briefcase represents
Marsellus Wallace's soul.

13:12.166 --> 13:13.876
Who told you that?
Woody or Buzz?

13:13.876 --> 13:15.712
Excuse me?
The answer is diamonds!

13:15.712 --> 13:17.839
S‐O ‐‐ "Sore loser much?"

13:17.839 --> 13:19.132
You want to go?

13:19.132 --> 13:20.466
Whoa, whoa, whoa.
No, no, no, no.

13:20.466 --> 13:22.635
Okay, guys, listen.
This is a game, not a brawl.

13:22.635 --> 13:25.430
"Maybe we want a brawl."

13:25.430 --> 13:26.723
I know I do.

13:26.723 --> 13:28.266
[ All exclaiming ]
Wait, no, no, no, listen.

13:28.266 --> 13:29.600
Whoa, whoa, whoa,
whoa, whoa, whoa!

13:29.600 --> 13:31.185
Hey, guys, guys, listen.
You guys aren't gonna fight.

13:32.687 --> 13:36.232
Though, I suppose
it's not my place

13:36.232 --> 13:37.942
to tell you
what's right or wrong.

13:37.942 --> 13:40.194
I'm just
the playing‐field leveler.

13:40.194 --> 13:41.738
Hmm.

13:41.738 --> 13:45.700
What accommodations can I devise
to allow these gorgeous youths

13:45.700 --> 13:49.203
an equal‐opportunity
death match?

13:49.203 --> 13:50.663
It's just stressful,
you know?

13:50.663 --> 13:52.582
Knowing that if I ever lose
her hearing aid,

13:52.582 --> 13:54.250
there's only one backup.

13:54.250 --> 13:56.878
Yeah, I‐I think we've all
got stories like this ‐‐

13:56.878 --> 13:58.838
stress
and helplessness ‐‐

13:58.838 --> 14:02.425
which is why it's important
to make time for ourselves.

14:02.425 --> 14:05.553
Now, fellas,
what do <i>you</i> want to do?

14:07.764 --> 14:10.600
I want to do a jigsaw puzzle
by myself.

14:10.600 --> 14:13.561
I want to make pancakes
with the mixings I decide.

14:13.561 --> 14:16.898
I want to be tired,
put something I don't
care about on TV,

14:16.898 --> 14:19.609
and ‐‐ and let the loud noises
startle me awake.

14:19.609 --> 14:20.359
Like, uh...

14:20.359 --> 14:21.486
Aah!

14:21.486 --> 14:22.862
Aahh!

14:22.862 --> 14:23.821
I want to dance.

14:23.821 --> 14:26.074
Sounds like a dad party.

14:26.074 --> 14:29.368
Voilà.
10‐minute tiramisu.

14:29.368 --> 14:32.205
Sorry, Becca,
I hate to expose you as a fraud,

14:32.205 --> 14:33.998
but you made it
in nine minutes.

14:33.998 --> 14:35.917
[ Laughter ]
Oh!

14:35.917 --> 14:38.044
I just love edgy comedy.

14:38.044 --> 14:39.629
Oh, um,
before everybody leaves,

14:39.629 --> 14:41.506
make sure to take
a homemade preserve.

14:41.506 --> 14:42.381
They're from this ‐‐

14:42.381 --> 14:44.217
Yeah, yeah, okay.
Let's head back.

14:44.217 --> 14:45.301
Everyone's waiting for us.

14:45.301 --> 14:46.636
I'm gonna take a walk.

14:46.636 --> 14:48.971
This hibiscus lemonade
went straight through me.

14:48.971 --> 14:51.599
Oh, sure, um, I'll take you
to the water closet.

14:51.599 --> 14:52.725
The crapper.
Yeah, right?

14:52.725 --> 14:53.810
Thanks, chief.

14:53.810 --> 14:56.562
Shall we?
I want to stay here.

14:56.562 --> 14:57.522
Me too.

14:57.522 --> 14:58.773
I'm not leaving.
Me neither.

14:58.773 --> 15:00.441
Carly: I'm not even
leaving this pantry.

15:00.441 --> 15:02.485
What do I have
to go back to?!

15:02.485 --> 15:05.029
God, don't let her to make you
feel bad about yourselves.

15:05.029 --> 15:06.614
We should.

15:06.614 --> 15:10.493
I am wearing my son's
bathing suit as underwear.

15:10.493 --> 15:13.704
And that is not okay.
Why did you tell us it was okay?

15:13.704 --> 15:14.956
Go without us, Maya.

15:14.956 --> 15:17.375
No, I don't like
how she makes you feel.

15:17.375 --> 15:20.837
And I really don't like
how she makes <i>me</i> feel.

15:20.837 --> 15:22.380
Now, our lives
are filled with chaos,

15:22.380 --> 15:24.841
and I've made my peace
with that.

15:24.841 --> 15:27.677
But if she's able to do
everything that we do

15:27.677 --> 15:31.180
and have this, then we must
be doing something wrong,

15:31.180 --> 15:32.390
and I can't accept that.

15:33.891 --> 15:35.768
I am the better mother.

15:35.768 --> 15:37.186
I have to be.

15:37.186 --> 15:40.314
Mom, look.
Becca gave me a French braid.

15:40.314 --> 15:42.275
I thought you said I didn't have
the right hair for it.

15:42.275 --> 15:45.528
Right. You!
Get the hell out of our lives.

15:45.528 --> 15:47.113
Wha?

15:47.113 --> 15:49.115
Um...

15:49.115 --> 15:54.245
You are welcome
to show yourselves out.

15:56.330 --> 15:58.708
[ Clears throat ]
Excuse me.

15:58.708 --> 15:59.667
Thanks for coming.
[ Jars rattling ]

15:59.667 --> 16:01.210
Thanks for coming.

16:01.210 --> 16:04.172
Thanks for coming.
Thank you.

16:08.926 --> 16:10.011
What? I'm supposed
to feel bad now?

16:10.011 --> 16:11.721
[ Sighs ]
God.

16:11.721 --> 16:13.556
Fine.

16:13.556 --> 16:15.099
Oh.

16:15.099 --> 16:16.726
Sorry.

16:16.726 --> 16:19.061
That was harsh.
I know you were trying to help.

16:19.061 --> 16:20.771
I just thought
you were judging me

16:20.771 --> 16:23.357
and that you think
you're better than me.

16:23.357 --> 16:25.776
I was...

16:25.776 --> 16:27.486
because I do.

16:27.486 --> 16:28.946
What?

16:28.946 --> 16:30.323
Yeah.

16:30.323 --> 16:32.825
Wait, is this
"Special‐Needs Mom Punk'd"?

16:32.825 --> 16:34.160
‐Mnh‐mnh.
‐Is it?

16:34.160 --> 16:35.369
No, because
I already had that idea,

16:35.369 --> 16:36.495
and I have it
written down.

16:36.495 --> 16:39.332
I know you.
I know a million yous.

16:39.332 --> 16:42.168
One more special‐needs mom
who thinks I have a problem

16:42.168 --> 16:44.295
because I‐I like
a little bit of order.

16:44.295 --> 16:46.339
"There's Becca.
She's not like us.

16:46.339 --> 16:48.966
She doesn't use horse manure
as shampoo."

16:51.594 --> 16:52.887
[ Lids popping ]

16:52.887 --> 16:55.014
What are you doing?
I'm unsealing your grains.

16:55.014 --> 16:56.098
[ Lids clicking, popping ]
Stop it.

16:56.098 --> 16:57.558
Leave my cereals
out of this.

16:57.558 --> 16:59.352
I will not.
I hate your bloody cereal.

16:59.352 --> 17:00.770
I hate your house.
I hate your tarp.

17:00.770 --> 17:02.104
I hate your mess.
Oh, do you?

17:02.104 --> 17:03.189
Oh, look,
have some mess.

17:03.189 --> 17:04.065
No!

17:04.065 --> 17:05.816
Here you are ‐‐
on your head.

17:05.816 --> 17:08.903
Wait, it's all
bloody vacuum‐sealed.

17:08.903 --> 17:11.239
Yes, they are ‐‐ for freshness,
as well as aesthetic purposes.

17:11.239 --> 17:13.407
You're aesthetic purposes.

17:13.407 --> 17:15.826
Wha‐‐ wha‐‐ Why?

17:15.826 --> 17:17.495
You are barbaric!

17:17.495 --> 17:20.706
This is the most unsatisfying
food fight I've ever had!

17:20.706 --> 17:22.708
Please, some scissors!

17:25.169 --> 17:27.380
Do you see what happens
when you make me apologize?

17:27.380 --> 17:29.757
So, this is my school.

17:29.757 --> 17:31.592
Did you know that
"school" and "prison"

17:31.592 --> 17:33.302
have the same number
of letters?

17:33.302 --> 17:34.428
Whoa.

17:34.428 --> 17:36.556
There's no way
that's a coincidence.

17:36.556 --> 17:39.058
Ooh, let's go in here
and make some art.

17:39.058 --> 17:42.103
Cool. Maybe we can use our
bodies as canvas or something.

17:42.103 --> 17:43.604
[ Doorknob rattles ]
Oh, poo.

17:43.604 --> 17:45.231
It's locked.

17:45.231 --> 17:48.025
You didn't say no
to body canvas.

17:48.025 --> 17:49.110
Is that still
on the table?

17:49.110 --> 17:51.404
Is that you?

17:51.404 --> 17:52.863
What?

17:52.863 --> 17:54.574
[ Scoffs ] No.

17:54.574 --> 17:58.202
It's ‐‐ it's some conformist
that ‐‐ that looks like me.

17:58.202 --> 18:00.079
Sometimes I'm tormented
by the thought

18:00.079 --> 18:01.872
that you're just
a big phony.

18:01.872 --> 18:03.583
I am not a phony.

18:03.583 --> 18:06.627
I am and always will be
a manic pixie dream boy.

18:06.627 --> 18:09.171
I want to believe you,
Ray of sunshine.

18:12.883 --> 18:13.801
Aaah!

18:13.801 --> 18:16.137
[ Glass shatters ]

18:16.137 --> 18:17.138
What was that?!

18:17.138 --> 18:20.349
Me proving
I'm a fun free spirit?

18:20.349 --> 18:23.144
Art is fun.
Spinning on a hilltop is fun.

18:23.144 --> 18:25.646
Felonies are not fun!

18:25.646 --> 18:28.274
Spinning isn't that fun.

18:28.274 --> 18:31.319
[ Door opens, closes ]
Oh, no.

18:31.319 --> 18:33.946
Dylan:
Adults, you've had your turn.
I'm going to fix this.

18:33.946 --> 18:38.117
So I call this meeting
of the special‐needs moms'
support group to order.

18:38.117 --> 18:39.368
‐Nope.
‐Worth a shot.

18:41.579 --> 18:43.914
So it seems like you two
make each other feel bad.

18:43.914 --> 18:45.291
Why?

18:45.291 --> 18:48.169
Mom, no can do your job
better than you.

18:48.169 --> 18:53.049
And, you, lady, if your kids are
1/10 as chewy as your cookies,

18:53.049 --> 18:55.718
they're gonna be all right.

18:55.718 --> 18:59.180
We do judge ourselves against
each other ‐‐ harshly.

18:59.180 --> 19:01.974
We want to believe that we're
the best moms for out kids.

19:01.974 --> 19:06.228
It's terrifying when it seems
like someone else is better.

19:06.228 --> 19:07.438
You know,
I think we need

19:07.438 --> 19:10.024
to give each other
and ourselves a break.

19:10.024 --> 19:12.652
It's like, we have
the same problems, right?

19:12.652 --> 19:15.196
We just come at them
from different angles.

19:15.196 --> 19:17.615
And I kind of like
some of your angles.

19:17.615 --> 19:19.700
[ Sighs ]

19:19.700 --> 19:20.576
For you.

19:20.576 --> 19:21.786
Oh.
[ Lid pops ]

19:21.786 --> 19:23.329
I love it.

19:23.329 --> 19:25.206
And I like your tarp.

19:25.206 --> 19:27.667
We're sisters.
We're not enemies.

19:27.667 --> 19:29.043
Yeah, there don't need
to be enemies.

19:29.043 --> 19:29.835
‐That's right.
‐Unh‐unh.

19:29.835 --> 19:31.379
No.
Uh...

19:31.379 --> 19:34.173
except moms
without special‐needs kids.

19:34.173 --> 19:35.716
Oh, they can kiss my ass.

19:35.716 --> 19:36.926
[ All agreeing ]

19:36.926 --> 19:38.928
Stuff them.
They just don't get it at all.

19:38.928 --> 19:41.389
[ All screaming ]

19:41.389 --> 19:44.558
♪♪

19:44.558 --> 19:47.103
[ Scattered laughter,
indistinct shouting ]

19:48.521 --> 19:51.565
Can you imagine
a weirder party?

19:51.565 --> 19:53.234
<i>♪ Louie, Louie ♪</i>

19:53.234 --> 19:54.944
<i>♪ Aye‐yi‐yi‐yi ♪</i>
[ All cheering ]

19:54.944 --> 19:56.779
<i>♪ Me gotta go ♪</i>

19:56.779 --> 19:57.947
<i>♪ Oh, no ♪</i>

19:57.947 --> 19:59.073
[ Group chanting "Go!" ]

19:59.073 --> 20:01.033
<i>♪ Louie, Louie ♪</i>

20:01.033 --> 20:02.827
<i>♪ Oh, baby ♪</i>

20:02.827 --> 20:04.495
<i>♪ Me gotta go ♪</i>

20:05.663 --> 20:08.999
Dance, you beautiful husbands,
da‐a‐ance!

20:08.999 --> 20:10.751
All the way, JJ.
Come on.

20:10.751 --> 20:11.877
Hold the body.

20:12.712 --> 20:15.172
Uh, hello, moms.

20:15.172 --> 20:16.966
[ Screaming stops ]

20:16.966 --> 20:19.760
Kenneth, did you give
our disabled children weapons

20:19.760 --> 20:21.804
so they could fight each other
and you could film it?

20:21.804 --> 20:23.264
No, I'm the good guy!

20:23.264 --> 20:24.932
This is
an inclusivity thing.

20:24.932 --> 20:26.350
I empowered them to battle.

20:26.350 --> 20:28.602
Some of them
I blindfolded,

20:28.602 --> 20:32.148
and some
I ‐‐ I duct‐taped.

20:32.148 --> 20:33.190
Hmm.

20:33.190 --> 20:36.569
How do I get myself
to stop talking?

20:36.569 --> 20:39.572
[ Indistinct conversations ]

20:39.572 --> 20:41.073
Okay.
We're leaving.

20:41.073 --> 20:42.241
Put the chairs
in the trunk.

20:42.241 --> 20:43.033
You got it, hon.

20:45.035 --> 20:46.370
[ Quietly ] I'm gonna put these
in the back seat.

20:46.370 --> 20:49.790
Woman: Oh, thank you.
Oh.

20:49.790 --> 20:53.252
Ray,
I have to say goodbye.

20:53.252 --> 20:55.880
You're way too wild and free
for me.

20:55.880 --> 20:58.132
I swear, I'm lame.

20:58.132 --> 20:59.508
Ask anyone.

20:59.508 --> 21:01.469
Nice try, Ray of sunshine.

21:01.469 --> 21:02.887
I know the real you.

21:02.887 --> 21:04.597
But here, take this.

21:16.567 --> 21:18.611
[ Voice breaking ] First,
I'd like to thank my family.
